They are a bunch of high schoolers who I mentor to

00:00:23.590 --> 00:00:29.170
build robots, and they're competing this weekend, so I

00:00:29.210 --> 00:00:31.500
had to represent.

00:00:31.500 --> 00:00:31.600
Yeah.

00:00:31.600 --> 00:00:33.940
I came into design through Georgia Tech's industrial design program.

00:00:33.940 --> 00:00:36.060
That's sort of how I got involved in this space and

00:00:36.060 --> 00:00:38.320
research, and I want to bring some more of that here

00:00:38.380 --> 00:00:39.360
to the atmosphere.

00:00:39.360 --> 00:00:43.410
So affordances, big weird word that maybe we don't

00:00:43.410 --> 00:00:47.220
talk much about outside of design, but basically what it means

00:00:47.220 --> 00:00:50.850
is the possible actions that an actor or person can perceive readily

00:00:50.850 --> 00:00:52.250
within the environment.

00:00:53.700 --> 00:00:57.210
So, for instance, stairs afford sitting, climbing to an

00:00:57.210 --> 00:01:00.840
able-bodied person, but to a wheelchair user,

00:01:00.860 --> 00:01:02.260
they do not afford climbing.

00:01:02.260 --> 00:01:07.550
That's because an affordance represents specifically a relationship between the

00:01:07.550 --> 00:01:09.160
individual and the environment.

00:01:09.160 --> 00:01:12.400
You don't just have a capability, but in a relationship

00:01:12.440 --> 00:01:14.960
with the person in that space, you have an affordance

00:01:14.960 --> 00:01:15.180
.

00:01:15.180 --> 00:01:20.340
So a capability without a signifier or without being self-

00:01:20.340 --> 00:01:24.160
evident of the environment itself is not actionable by the user

00:01:24.160 --> 00:01:27.490
and therefore not a real affordance that results in actions to

00:01:27.490 --> 00:01:28.680
be able to be taken.

00:01:28.890 --> 00:01:33.310
Now, we in AppProto are familiar with lots of

00:01:33.490 --> 00:01:36.660
really great capabilities that we have in the atmosphere.

00:01:36.680 --> 00:01:38.600
You've got decoupling of data and apps.

00:01:38.600 --> 00:01:41.640
You can reuse that data across lots of different places.

00:01:41.660 --> 00:01:45.020
You sort of have this headless website that anyone can build

00:01:45.020 --> 00:01:46.300
an interface for.

00:01:46.350 --> 00:01:49.300
There's no real first-party claim to data.

00:01:49.320 --> 00:01:52.830
You can delete stuff, maybe, because you're also really

00:01:52.830 --> 00:01:55.880
publishing to the web, but we as users now have a

00:01:55.880 --> 00:01:58.800
lot more agency than we used to have on centralized platforms,

00:01:58.800 --> 00:02:01.290
and we can exert market forces in a way that we couldn

00:02:01.290 --> 00:02:04.100
't before, and we can move around without losing anything in

00:02:04.190 --> 00:02:04.920
the process.

00:02:04.950 --> 00:02:10.020
These are really cool capabilities, but if you don't manifest

00:02:10.020 --> 00:02:13.840
those into perceivable actions, there are not affordances.

00:02:13.840 --> 00:02:17.220
The user, the person, cannot do those things.

00:02:17.240 --> 00:02:21.620
The agency that we're trying to provide won't be executed

00:02:21.660 --> 00:02:24.450
, so we need to make those executable.

00:02:24.700 --> 00:02:30.530
We can elevate capabilities into affordances, and help people establish

00:02:30.530 --> 00:02:35.210
new mental models around all these affordances by doing good product

00:02:35.220 --> 00:02:36.040
design.

00:02:36.060 --> 00:02:39.100
So let's see some examples, because people are doing a

00:02:39.120 --> 00:02:41.240
great job here in the atmosphere.

00:02:41.250 --> 00:02:43.310
I, as an AppProto user, can use my

00:02:43.310 --> 00:02:46.780
account in lots of different places, not just blue skies.

00:02:46.800 --> 00:02:49.180
So this is the login screen for Pocket.

00:02:49.180 --> 00:02:52.840
We've got a couple signifiers, like the little butterfly

00:02:52.840 --> 00:02:57.430
, and user handle to indicate that my blue sky identity is

00:02:57.470 --> 00:02:59.520
usable in this place.

00:02:59.550 --> 00:03:03.070
Shout out to Amelia and FedCM for working on making

00:03:03.070 --> 00:03:06.750
this user experience even better in the future.

00:03:06.970 --> 00:03:09.640
I can use my AppProto account for all different kinds

00:03:09.640 --> 00:03:12.470
of activity, not just skeeting.

00:03:12.500 --> 00:03:15.450
So this is SkyReader, which is an atmospheric R

00:03:15.450 --> 00:03:19.260
SS reader, and they added the ability to save articles to

00:03:19.260 --> 00:03:21.670
Semble, or Margin, which is a bookmark

00:03:21.670 --> 00:03:23.800
ing service on the atmosphere.

00:03:23.820 --> 00:03:26.480
And what's cool about that, we all know that the

00:03:26.480 --> 00:03:30.680
permissionless open access of the network means that you can kind

00:03:30.680 --> 00:03:31.800
of just build stuff.

00:03:31.820 --> 00:03:34.440
So Ronan here, the CEO of Semble and Cos

00:03:34.440 --> 00:03:37.180
mic Network, had no idea they were building this and required

00:03:37.180 --> 00:03:37.800
no intervention.

00:03:37.820 --> 00:03:40.140
So he found out alongside the rest of us, and is

00:03:40.200 --> 00:03:41.800
like, "Cool, I'm excited to try it."

00:03:41.820 --> 00:03:47.480
I can interact with people on different services.

00:03:47.500 --> 00:03:50.000
So this is a clip from the Witch Sky Client,

00:03:50.010 --> 00:03:52.480
which is a blue sky client fork of Social App.

00:03:52.500 --> 00:03:56.460
They add these helpful little badges next to people's names of

00:03:56.460 --> 00:03:58.480
what PDS service they're using.

00:03:58.500 --> 00:03:59.660
So I can see Dr.

00:03:59.670 --> 00:04:02.050
K's post, and I can see also that she is

00:04:02.130 --> 00:04:03.480
on the Black Sky PDS.

00:04:03.500 --> 00:04:06.300
And even though we're on different services, we can still

00:04:06.300 --> 00:04:11.900
engage and follow and interact with each other totally normally.

00:04:12.080 --> 00:04:14.480
I can even interact with people across different protocols.

00:04:14.500 --> 00:04:17.060
We just heard from Anuj all the great things Bridgie

00:04:17.060 --> 00:04:17.720
is doing.

00:04:17.740 --> 00:04:21.170
So I can see everything on his Macedon account get brid

00:04:21.170 --> 00:04:26.480
ged all the way across and interact in a perfectly native way

00:04:26.570 --> 00:04:27.040
.

00:04:27.050 --> 00:04:30.130
I can engage with the same activity in different places.

00:04:30.260 --> 00:04:33.810
You might have been assembling your conference schedule today using SmokeS

00:04:33.870 --> 00:04:35.460
ignal or Atmo.

00:04:35.530 --> 00:04:38.160
rsvp or on the official conference website.

00:04:38.180 --> 00:04:41.500
All of that is pulling from the same activity, the same

00:04:41.500 --> 00:04:43.920
data on the atmosphere, and that's why we're able

00:04:43.920 --> 00:04:48.520
to get multiple different experiences that might work better for different people

00:04:48.520 --> 00:04:49.320
.

00:04:49.330 --> 00:04:52.560
I can even move my account without losing anything in the process

00:04:52.560 --> 00:04:52.800
.

00:04:52.820 --> 00:04:55.680
So we've had a lot of successful migrations to Euros

00:04:55.680 --> 00:04:57.560
ky, which is very exciting.

00:04:57.580 --> 00:05:01.140
The EU haul tool is really usable, and we have totally

00:05:01.210 --> 00:05:06.440
normal users happy and satisfied with their moving process, and again

00:05:06.440 --> 00:05:10.480
, you can interact with them all just the same.

00:05:10.500 --> 00:05:14.470
This one I like a lot too, because obviously some projects

00:05:14.470 --> 00:05:15.160
end.

00:05:15.180 --> 00:05:17.600
Every product doesn't last forever.

00:05:17.620 --> 00:05:21.170
Some people might remember the original Skylight, not Tori

00:05:21.250 --> 00:05:22.520
, but Skylights.

00:05:22.540 --> 00:05:25.520
Which was a film reviewing app on the atmosphere, which the

00:05:25.520 --> 00:05:28.540
maintainer decided was, you know, they were not done

00:05:28.540 --> 00:05:31.380
, or they were done with that project, which is okay

00:05:31.400 --> 00:05:31.580
.

00:05:31.720 --> 00:05:35.480
They could build a tool to allow people to migrate their data

00:05:35.480 --> 00:05:37.800
out of Skylights and into PopFeed, which is

00:05:37.800 --> 00:05:41.080
another film reviewing app on the atmosphere, and so all that

00:05:41.080 --> 00:05:43.740
data gets to live on.

00:05:43.760 --> 00:05:45.540
Skylights is able to go to rest, but all the

00:05:45.540 --> 00:05:49.310
people and the users and their reviews and data get to continue

00:05:49.360 --> 00:05:52.500
to be useful in the atmosphere.

00:05:52.520 --> 00:05:53.960
This is a weird one.

00:05:53.980 --> 00:05:57.050
My social activity doesn't necessarily need an app.

00:05:57.120 --> 00:05:59.100
So, some of you might be familiar with Teal,

00:05:59.100 --> 00:06:03.260
but if you're not, it is an atmospheric alternative to

00:06:03.260 --> 00:06:06.190
LastFM, which is a music scrabbling service

00:06:06.310 --> 00:06:11.340
where you can log your listening activity across Spotify, Apple Music

00:06:11.340 --> 00:06:14.550
, Tidal, you know, whatever you use so that

00:06:14.660 --> 00:06:19.640
we can have social music discovery features outside of an individual streaming

00:06:19.640 --> 00:06:20.320
service.

00:06:20.380 --> 00:06:23.160
Teal is like that for the atmosphere, so you can

00:06:23.160 --> 00:06:25.580
scrabble all of your listens to your PDS,

00:06:25.710 --> 00:06:29.290
and then we get all the atmospheric advantages where people can build

00:06:29.290 --> 00:06:34.030
visualizations and wraps and all those things, but Teal

00:06:34.110 --> 00:06:35.490
doesn't exist.

00:06:35.520 --> 00:06:36.800
It's not a product.

00:06:36.850 --> 00:06:38.840
This is the website.

00:06:38.860 --> 00:06:42.400
It just says coming soon eventually.

00:06:42.420 --> 00:06:44.450
Bailey and Zeyu and all of them are busy with

00:06:44.450 --> 00:06:47.280
other things, so keep working on it, but maybe we

00:06:47.290 --> 00:06:50.190
'll get Teal eventually, but not yet, but it

00:06:50.190 --> 00:06:51.640
's the atmosphere.

00:06:51.660 --> 00:06:52.740
You can just do things.

00:06:52.770 --> 00:06:53.800
Somebody made Teal.

00:06:53.830 --> 00:06:54.800
There it is.

00:06:54.820 --> 00:06:55.800
It's not at Teal.

00:06:55.800 --> 00:06:58.380
fm, but this is a full Teal experience where

00:06:58.460 --> 00:07:02.460
you can see genres and activity and trending and I can see

00:07:02.610 --> 00:07:05.530
what people are listening to.

00:07:05.580 --> 00:07:09.580
So we've really barely started to manifest all the possible afford

00:07:09.770 --> 00:07:13.860
ances with these great capabilities that we have.

00:07:13.880 --> 00:07:18.260
How might we, as a community, overcome the hurdles preventing

00:07:18.470 --> 00:07:22.500
the mass adoption and, importantly, the execution of agency made

00:07:22.540 --> 00:07:25.740
possible by liberatory network technology?

00:07:25.840 --> 00:07:31.930
I think we need more designers, more researchers, ethnographers

00:07:31.930 --> 00:07:35.820
, system thinkers, humanities experts to help make all these afford

00:07:35.820 --> 00:07:39.940
ances legible, to help people establish new mental models around

00:07:39.960 --> 00:07:44.800
all these affordances, and really to make the agency afford

00:07:44.860 --> 00:07:49.010
ed by all this decentralized technology accessible to people so they can

00:07:49.010 --> 00:07:50.240
exercise that agency.

00:07:50.270 --> 00:07:51.240
Whoo!

00:07:51.270 --> 00:07:52.240
Whoo!

00:07:52.270 --> 00:07:53.240
Whoo!

00:07:53.270 --> 00:07:54.240
Whoo!

00:07:54.270 --> 00:07:55.240
Whoo!

00:07:55.270 --> 00:08:00.240
So that's what we're doing.

00:08:00.240 --> 00:08:02.550
Ecosystem Action Research, you might have heard of us

00:08:02.550 --> 00:08:05.110
in the last month or so, is a little band of

00:08:05.110 --> 00:08:08.620
volunteers, I think we're at 13 now, of those

00:08:08.800 --> 00:08:12.510
types of people, we're going to try to bring more

00:08:12.510 --> 00:08:17.250
research and design activity to this space and facilitate these discovery processes

00:08:17.290 --> 00:08:20.840
alongside the community with the community to answer some of these big

00:08:20.890 --> 00:08:23.950
ecosystem-wide questions.

00:08:23.990 --> 00:08:29.110
What we envision in the long term is that the atmosphere network

00:08:29.110 --> 00:08:35.790
ecosystem contributors and participants are empowered to exercise the agency afforded

00:08:35.840 --> 00:08:39.330
by a public interest internet, and that includes all sorts of

00:08:39.330 --> 00:08:43.440
people like moderators and knowledge workers and organizers and artists,

00:08:43.440 --> 00:08:48.530
journalists, builders like you, and just everyday end-us

00:08:48.650 --> 00:08:49.180
ers.

00:08:49.200 --> 00:08:52.270
So our mission at EAR is to equip and support the

00:08:52.390 --> 00:08:56.810
people and organizations who build with and on top of the app

00:08:56.810 --> 00:09:02.160
network technology to empower people who create on and organize with and

00:09:02.160 --> 00:09:05.800
steward trust and safety for internet communities.

00:09:05.820 --> 00:09:10.610
I want to thank Dan for encouraging me to make this talk

